<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="351" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="351">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="351">
The genus is treated as Latin masculine and is a combination incorporating the Greek abaco, being broad and therefore like the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Abax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Abax" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="351" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Abax</taxonomicName>
, and phrastos meaning 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“expression”">&quot;expression&quot;</normalizedToken>
. Given that these species are similar and related to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Abacomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Abacomorphus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="351" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Abacomorphus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Abacoleptus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Abacoleptus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="351" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Abacoleptus</taxonomicName>
, the name roughly translates as yet &quot;another expression of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Abax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Abax" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="351" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Abax</taxonomicName>
.&quot;
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
